  <title>
   <narrative xml:lang="EN">Lifesaving Nutrition Intervention and Response to the Humanitarian Crisis in the Northeastern States</narrative>
  </title>
  <description type="4">
   <narrative xml:lang="EN">Action Against Hunger will admit children with severe acute malnutrition (SAM) to therapeutic nutrition programs. Additionally, the organization will mass screen for healthy nutrition practices, and provide children and pregnant and lactating women (PLW) with infant and young children feeding (IYCF) counseling sessions.  

At least 23% of IDP households are headed by women and 40% of IDP women are pregnant and lactating, requiring special nutrition support. Access to activities will be routinely monitored through spot checks, discussions with communities, etc. and obstacles to equal access will be promptly addressed. Due to illiteracy being significantly higher among women than men (77.8% of women in Borno are illiterate, compared to 58.3% of men), the program will integrate IEC materials adapted to illiteracy (introducing simple drawings, messages in Hausa) within communications.</narrative>
  </description>
  <description type="1">
   <narrative xml:lang="EN">Despite the start of the main harvest season, the Armed Opposition Group conflict continues to limit accessibility, humanitarian assistance, livelihoods and markets in parts of Borno and Yobe States. Yobe states. Mass MUAC screenings from the last six months continue to indicate a nutrition emergency in recently accessible localities, including Bama, Banki, Monguno, Konduga, Gamboru and Ngala in Borno state and Tarmuwa, Gujba and Gulani in Yobe as well as in select internally displaced persons (IDP) camps in MMC and Jere LGA. In these areas, the proportion of children screened indicated global acute malnutrition (GAM) ranged from 20 to nearly 60 percent.</narrative>
  </description>
